<DOC><DOCNO> AP880218-0126 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-88 1218EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Reagan-Lithuania 1stLd-Writethru a0623 02-18 0224</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Reagan-Lithuania, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,220</SECOND><HEAD>Reagan Signs Lithuanian Independence Resolution</HEAD><NOTE>EDs: Recasts first two grafs to reflect that Independence Day wasTuesday of this week; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng, `Then, in.'</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan has signed legislationdesignating Tuesday of this week as Lithuanian Independence Day,saying the United States will never recognize the ``forcibleincorporation'' of Lithuania into the Soviet Union.   In a proclamation signed last week, Reagan said Lithuaniaenjoyed ``political and religious freedom for all citizens''following its declaration of independence on Feb. 16, 1918.   ``Then, in June 1940, the year after the signing of theMolotov-Ribbentrop Pact, the Soviet Union invaded and illegallyoccupied Lithuania and the other Baltic States,'' the presidentsaid.   ``The United States unequivocally condemned this violation ofnational sovereignty and national integrity, and ever since thenour policy has remained consistent. We have never recognized theforcible incorporation of Lithuania into the Soviet Union, and wenever will,'' Reagan said.   Police and civilian auxiliary officers prevented Lithuaniansfrom celebrating the 70th anniversaru of their short-livedindependence on Tuesday, and activists said four Lithuaniannationalists were put under house arrest.   Thirty-two U.S. senators have written to Soviet Leader MikhailS. Gorbachev asking him not to interfere with planneddemonstrations and religious services this week in the Sovietrepublics of Lithuania and Eastonia.</TEXT></DOC>